<TEXTAREA NAME="ReplyMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">[QUOTE]Originally posted by Gorgash:
[B]A few comments:

1. "...playing the game in the preferred manner easier, safer, faster, or more profitable..." 

I agree that I don't think things should be made easier. That's the lazy man's way out.

2. To SolClaryn, who says: "Or another option, put MORE of the same level dungeons/camps in the game."

   Personally, I think there's plenty of places to hunt at the same levels. People tend to get stuck hunting in the same places, while dozens of camps go UNPLAYED. I have hunted in Lesser Fay an orc camp, that never once in my over a dozen visits, has EVER been camped. I have hunted Kerra Isle, levels 10-25 or so, and in the entire ZONE I have never seen more than two others outside of my group. There's dozens of such examples. To say there are not enough places just means you need to look around more.

3. To DJAVulkai, who says: "In any case, my point is that the game ought to be evened out a bit more. At 26th level, i still and kinda afraid of going into BlackBurrow, even though i would not get exp for ~anything~ there, they can still wipe the floor with me."

"That ain't right"

Personally, I don't think there's anything wrong with this. D&D's system was totally flawed anyway. I mean come on, according to the old rules a 25th level fighter could jump off of a 4,000 foot cliff, land, dust himself off, and proceed to singlehandedly destroy an army or 3,000 orcs. And you use that as a basis for comparison?

You walk into a gnoll lair at 26, you SHOULD have SOME fear. Numbers do account for something.

4. To dearjohn, who says: "Some of the reasons I have seen on the boards for suspending accounts would lead to a lawsuit if they tried it on me. These people need to wake up and realize this is JUST A GAME. "

Excuse me but, you want people to realize it's JUST A GAME, while simultaneously threaten a LAWSUIT? C'mon guy, a little consistency would make a more powerful argument.

Also, you say:

"Anyway, enough ranting, EQ will quickly fade away as some of the more customer-responsive games in beta reach the open market. Then I suspect Brad and Gordon and company will be left sitting there wondering what happened."

Rant away all you want, it's your right after all. But if you don't like the game that much, go play something else. Just how many of your ideas would you like to see in the game for your whole $10 per month? Personally, I don't have any major complaints with the game whatsoever. It's still the most enjoyable game out there for me, and I have no plans on leaving.

Lastly,

5. To Rylius, who says: "Later I elaborated on the idea. And this I really like. Why not make the zone reproduceable. Every group that enters a particular dungeon gets an instance of that dungeon all for that group. If another group enters the same dungeon, another instance of the zone is created on the server for that group. Ok, not realistic, but would definitely give you that dungeon feel - hands down!"

A nice idea, but one that I think would be hugely unpopular. You wouldn't be able to just go explore a new dungeon at all unless you rounded up a group first, and it's harder to find people to group with when you don't know the dungeon at all. It would also make it impossible to find a group AFTER you've entered a dungeon. And when a group lost a member or two, they might be FORCED to exit the dungeon to try to find replacements, meanwhile having JUST MISSED some others calling out to group that left the zone after not having found someone, knowing it's impossible to get a group while INSIDE the dungeon.

Another example: Say I want to take my level 17 bard, and risk his life heading down to Lower Guk to get the Mask of Deception, a drop that is lore and no drop so often poofs. I don't think that choice should be made an impossibility for me.

Just a few offhand observations about that.
[/B][/QUOTE]

</TEXTAREA>
